[Patient] How much water should I drink each day to manage my heart failure?
[Healthcare Educator] Aim for around 1.5 to 2 liters of fluids daily, but consult with your doctor for specific recommendations.
[Patient] I struggle to keep track of how much I drink. Any tips?
[Healthcare Educator] Try using a regular cup or bottle with markings to measure your fluids each day.
[Patient] That sounds helpful, but I can't afford to buy a special cup.
[Healthcare Educator] You can make your own markings on a regular cup or bottle at home to track your intake.
[Patient] Will monitoring my fluid intake really make a difference in my heart failure management?
[Healthcare Educator] Yes, monitoring your fluid intake can help prevent fluid overload and improve your heart health.
[Patient] How do I know if I'm drinking too much fluid?
[Healthcare Educator] Watch out for symptoms like swelling, shortness of breath, and sudden weight gain. 
[Patient] What should I do if I notice these symptoms?
[Healthcare Educator] Contact your doctor immediately if you experience any of these symptoms. 
[Patient] Can I drink any type of fluid, or are some better than others?
[Healthcare Educator] Stick to water and limit your intake of sugary drinks and high-sodium beverages.
[Patient] I love my sweet tea, though. Is it okay to have it sometimes?
[Healthcare Educator] It's best to limit sugary drinks, but you can have a small amount occasionally. 
